              <p><font size=3D"2" face=3D"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-s=
erif"><b><font color=3D"#990000">FEATURE=20
                STORY -- OCA ALERT UPDATE: </font><br>
                USDA'S NEWEST SNEAK ATTACK ON ORGANIC STANDARDS</b><br>
                Thanks to all of you who joined thousands of organic consum=
ers=20
                in late May and signed OCA's petition to the USDA opposing =
the=20
                agency's latest &quot;Sneak Attack=
&quot; to allow 38 new no=
n-organic=20
                ingredients in products labeled as &quot;USDA Or=
ganic&quot;=
. <font size=3D"1">(Read=20
                full petition here: <a href=3D"http://alerts.organicconsume=
rs.org/trk/click?ref=3Dzqtbkk3um_1-b4x3147x3340774&" target=3D=
"_blank">htt=
p://www.organicconsumers.org/articles/article_5225.cfm</a>)</font></font></=
p>
              <p><font size=3D"2" face=3D"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-s=
erif">USDA's=20
                controversial proposal to allow 38 new non-organic ingredie=
nts=20
                in products labeled as &quot;organic=
&quot; has fueled the a=
nger=20
                of organic consumers and generated a backlash of negative p=
ress=20
                coast to coast. Over the weekend the New York Times and the=
 L.A.=20
                Times (as well as a number of other major news outlets) ran=
 feature=20
                stories on the debacle.</font></p>
              <p><font size=3D"2" face=3D"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-s=
erif">The=20
                New York Times noted that the mega-brewer Anheuser-Busch pr=
essured=20
                the USDA into allowing them to use hops grown with pesticid=
es=20
                and chemical fertilizers in their &quot;Organic =
Wild Hop La=
ger&quot;=20
                beer. In the Los Angeles Times, Ronnie Cummins, OCA's Natio=
nal=20
                Director, was quoted as saying, &quot;This propo=
sal is blat=
ant=20
                catering to powerful industry players who want the benefits=
 of=20
                labeling their products 'USDA organic' without doing the wo=
rk=20
                to source organic materials.&quot;</font></p>
              <p><font size=3D"2" face=3D"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-s=
erif">Although=20
                industry was given the better part of two years to work wit=
h the=20
                USDA in developing this proposal, the agency only gave the =
public=20
                a brief 7-day comment period. During that short time, the O=
CA=20
                generated over 8,000 petition signatures telling the USDA t=
o back=20
                off on allowing non-organic hops, factory-farmed animal int=
estines,=20
                tainted fish oil, and other problematic ingredients in orga=
nic=20
                products.</font></p>
              <p><font size=3D"2" face=3D"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-s=
erif">On=20
                Friday June 8, the USDA took its third swing at organic sta=
ndards=20
                and struck out, violating federal law by refusing to respon=
d to=20
                a federal court order to stop allowing companies to use the=
 38=20
                non-organic ingredients proposed for inclusion in products =
labeled=20
                &quot;USDA Organic&quot;. Unprepared =
for the firestorm of p=
rotest=20
                against their latest Sneak Attack, the USDA has been refusi=
ng=20
                to talk to the press.</font><br>
              </p>
              <p><font size=3D"2" face=3D"Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-s=
erif">=20
                </font> </p>
            </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td width=3D"17%" height=3D"153"><img src=3D"http://www.organic=
